Women will regret NOT doing these! Share now!

1.	Malasan to Vayu Nishkasana- Vayu Nishkasana (Gas Release Pose) is great for digestion, core strength, and menstrual health. Engages the core and stimulates digestion, aiding in weight management. Boosts metabolism through gentle abdominal compression. Repeat for 5-10 breaths, moving with your breath.

2.	Cat Cow pose- Supports Women’s Health (Pregnancy & Postpartum) During pregnancy, it improves spinal mobility and relieves lower back pain. Postpartum, it helps regain core strength and pelvic floor control. Repeat for 5-10 breaths, moving with your breath.

3.	Chakki Chalasana- Chakki Chalanasana (Churning the Mill Pose) is particularly beneficial for women, as it strengthens the core, improves digestion, and supports reproductive health. Beneficial for women trying to conceive by improving circulation in reproductive organs. Perform 10 rotations clockwise and 10 counterclockwise while maintaining a steady breath.

4.	Setu Bandhasana- Supports Reproductive & Menstrual Health, Stimulates the pelvic organs, improving blood flow to the uterus and ovaries, Helps regulate menstrual cycles and reduces cramps, Aids in managing symptoms of PCOS and hormonal imbalances. Hold for 30 seconds to 1 minute, breathing deeply.

5.	Devi Asana- Devi Asana (Goddess Pose) connects women to their inner Shakti (divine feminine energy). This pose is not just about physical strength but also about embracing confidence, grace, and intuition. It helps open the hips, activate the lower chakras, and restore balance between strength and softness. Hold for 30 seconds to 1 minute, visualizing yourself as a radiant, powerful goddess.

⚠️ Disclaimer: Always consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new exercise routine, especially if you have existing knee issues or concerns. This routine is general advice and may not be suitable for everyone. Listen to your body and modify as needed.

Teens today are busier than ever, juggling academics, extracurriculars, social lives, and digital distractions. This nonstop pace often leads to stress, poor posture, lack of exercise, and emotional ups and downs.

These asanas are simple, effective, and can be easily incorporated into a busy teen’s daily routine. Consistency is key for visible benefits in posture, height, and skin glow.

Follow @YogJourney for more

Timing-
Tadasana Walk: Hold for 20–60 seconds per set, repeat 2–3 times. Can be done daily, even multiple times a day.
Padmasana: Start with 1–5 minutes, gradually increasing as comfortable. Advanced: may hold up to 10 minutes.
Malasana: Hold for 30 seconds to 2 minutes per set, repeat 2–3 times. Advanced: up to 20 minutes if comfortable.
Baddha Konasana: Hold for 1–5 minutes, focusing on relaxed breathing.
Naukasana: Hold for 15–30 seconds per set, repeat 2–3 times. Gradually increase as strength improves.

By making these five asanas a daily habit, even for just a few minutes, busy teens can boost their physical health, mental clarity, emotional stability, and overall sense of well-being—helping them glow from within and supporting their natural growth

These 3 superfoods = natural sugar control. IMPORTANT to share! Don’t skip these if you’re diabetic! 🛑🧠

1. Makhana (Fox Nuts)
•Low glycemic index — won’t spike blood sugar quickly.
(Study: Journal of Food Science and Technology, 2016)
•Rich in magnesium, which supports insulin function and glucose uptake.
•High in protein and fiber, helping with satiety and blood sugar control.
•Packaged versions may be fried or salted — avoid.
•Daily intake: 1 cup (30–40g) roasted makhana daily is safe for most diabetics. Dry roast or use minimal ghee.
I buy Organic makhanas only from @pearl_mithila_makhana 

2. Broccoli
•Rich in sulforaphane, a compound that may reduce blood glucose levels by improving insulin sensitivity and lowering oxidative stress.
(Study: Science Translational Medicine, 2017)
•High in fiber, which slows digestion and prevents blood sugar spikes.
•Low in calories and carbs, making it ideal for glycemic control.
•Daily intake: 1 cup (100g) cooked or raw broccoli daily is safe and beneficial.

3. Chia Seeds
•High in soluble fiber, which forms a gel in the stomach, slowing down glucose absorption.
(Study: European Journal of Clinical Nutrition, 2009)
•Helps reduce inflammation and improve insulin sensitivity.
•Improves satiety, aiding in weight and appetite control — key for Type 2 diabetes.
•Caution: Can cause bloating or constipation if not soaked
•Daily intake: 1 to 2 tablespoons (15–30g) per day, ideally soaked in water

10 food combos— tasty & backed by science for better health!

1. Salt + Watermelon
Balances sodium and potassium, helping replenish electrolytes after sweating or exercise. Also supports hydration more effectively than water alone.

2. Almonds + Dark Chocolate
Combines flavonoids with healthy fats to support heart health and lower inflammation. Also boosts antioxidant intake and satiety.

3. Broccoli + Mustard Seeds
Myrosinase in mustard seeds enhances sulforaphane activation in broccoli, a powerful anti-cancer compound. This combo improves detoxification and cellular protection.

4. Blueberries + Greek Yogurt
Antioxidants in berries and probiotics in yogurt improve gut health and cognitive function. They also support immunity and digestive balance.

5. Apple + Peanut Butter
Pairing fiber-rich fruit with protein slows digestion and curbs blood sugar swings. It also makes a satisfying, balanced snack for energy control.

6. Milk + Dates
Natural sugars in dates combined with milk offer a nutrient-rich energy boost. Also provides iron, calcium, and essential B vitamins.

7. Coconut Water + Chia Seeds
Rehydrates while chia adds fiber, slowing sugar absorption and sustaining energy. Great for post-workout recovery and digestive health.

8. Green Tea + Lemon
Vitamin C in lemon preserves catechins in green tea, increasing antioxidant activity. This duo supports metabolism and immunity.

9. Ghee + Coffee
Healthy fats in ghee slow caffeine absorption, offering sustained energy and mental focus. Also supports gut lining and reduces acidity.

10. Boiled Egg + Raw Veggies
Fats in the egg yolk help absorb vitamins A, D, E, and K from veggies. This combo also supports vision, bone health, and immunity.

Early puberty in girls can also be triggered by genetics, obesity, high-fat diets, exposure to endocrine-disrupting chemicals or pollutants, poor sleep, inactivity, certain medications, and underlying health issues like hypothyroidism.

•  Avoid too much Milk (after age 2)
Commercial dairy cows are often treated with hormones like rBGH (recombinant bovine growth hormone) to boost milk production. Too much milk after age 2 can introduce animal hormones that may trigger early periods in girls. 

•  Say NO to Broiler chicken
Many studies link high intake of commercial animal products (including eggs and chicken) to early onset of puberty in girls, due to estrogenic substances or hormonal disruption. 

•  Keep her away from Family trauma
This is such an important—and often overlooked—topic. Emotional stress and family trauma can activate stress hormones that influence early puberty. A chaotic or unsafe environment may cause the body to mature faster. 

•  Limit exposure to grown up content
Sexualized or adult media can overstimulate young minds and contribute to early menarche. These exposures may signal the brain to mature too soon. Keep her entertainment age-appropriate to protect emotional and hormonal balance.

•  Avoid Perfumes & fragrances
Many scented products contain hormone-disrupting chemicals like phthalates. These can interfere with natural hormone function and lead to early periods. Use natural, fragrance-free options to keep her development safe and steady.

I’m using cast iron tawa, kadhai and neem wood spatulas from @duracast.india. 

1.Replace non stick tawa with a cast iron tawa - Ditch toxic Teflon and switch to a cast iron tawa that’s naturally non-stick, chemical-free, and boosts your iron intake.
It’s a durable, eco-friendly cookware choice that lasts generations and enhances food flavor.
2.Use steel lunch boxes instead of plastic dabbas for your kids. Plastic is plastic – no matter what. Plastic dabbas can leach harmful chemicals—stainless steel lunch boxes are toxin-free, safe, and sustainable.
They’re BPA-free, easy to clean, and keep your child’s food fresh and hygienic

3.Replace black plastic ladles with wooden ladles- Black plastic utensils may release microplastics and toxins when exposed to heat—neem wood ladles are safer and antibacterial.
They’re gentle on your cookware and bring an earthy, sustainable touch to your kitchen.

4.Swap aluminium kadhai with cast iron kadhai- Aluminium cookware can react with food and leach metals—cast iron kadhai is non-reactive, long-lasting, and health-friendly.
It’s a chemical-free cooking essential that retains heat evenly and enriches your meals with iron.
5.Invest in a steel chopping board over plastic/wooden- Say goodbye to bacterial build-up and microplastic shedding—stainless steel chopping boards are hygienic and ultra-durable.
They’re non-toxic, rust-resistant, and perfect for a clean, modern kitchen. Wooden boards require regular maintenance, including oiling and thorough sun drying, to prevent warping and bacterial growth. How often do you do that?
